If I told you to do 1 style of exercise for the rest of your life, 99% of you would tell me I'm an idiot. And you'd be right.
 
 
Same with your food, macros, & calories.
 
 
In this #25MinPhys I cover how a concept called “Periodized nutrition” would recommend alter your fat, protein, and carbohydrate intake based on different phases of the year (in-season, post-season, etc.) as well as different goals such as fat loss, muscle gain, peak performance, etc.
 
 
P.S. Hope you enjoy the impromptu uber-secret life hack at the end of this IG video…
 
 
Enjoy! - Andy

One of my favorite fight week stories ever happened 2 y ago this week....

 @officialmikelee brought me on the team to help him drop to super middleweight (168) for the 1st time ever for his IBF World Title fight. (Spoiler: fight did not go well for us.).

Mike started camp at 198 and was progressing PERFECTLY all camp. 

Weight cut culture in boxing is WAY different than MMA, so while he was hitting all the numbers (most days within ounces), he (and team) were super nervous. 

This resulting in bringing 2 scales to fight week. I've not seen that often, but whatever.

The DAY before hitting the scale, his Dad inexplicably SHATTTTTTERED not 1, but BOTH scales. To this day, I have absolutely no clue how he accomplished this. 

It was about 2 hours of pandemonium. We got a new one, he hit the weight with ease. 

BC boxing is weird, we had to weigh in the next day at 178. No problem. We get there and they use a scale about 40 y old, literally held together by 3 pound of duct tape. (Different scale than the day before). The scale says he's like 182 or something absurd. Of course, we throw a fit, pull all the tape off that horrid scale, and surprise, he's right on 178. 

Point being, even at the highest level, so things in pro sports are still shockingly amateur 🤣🤣. But holy F did that one have me 🤬🤬🤬. What a joke. 

If you work in sports, be ready for anything, roll with the punches - bc they're coming - and just keep executing no matter what.

Obviously, exercise should not be performed INSTEAD of therapy or counseling and "mental health" is far more involved than just 1-2 metrics (e.g., emotional well-being). The best course of action is almost surely a combination of both physical and mental work. Just don't forget about the physical part when possible.

node.text:
Here are some fun facts about your muscles. 

They are mainly preoccupied with metabolism, not contraction.

However, new research is challenging a lot of what we know (or think we know) about muscle physiology. This is the course of science if given enough time & energy, it autocorrects (usually). As technology gets better, the stories get refined or, in some cases, re-written entirely.
 
P.S. the red thing you’re looking at is a single muscle fiber from a healthy young human under a high-powered microscope. The vertical squiggly lines show you the smallest functional unit of a muscle, which we call a “sarcomere.” The blue circles are the nuclei, which hold your DNA and control the growth, death, repair, and general function of the cell. The green vertical lines I made in PPT as arbitrary lines to highlight the concept of how much of those proteins are made up of each given protein.
 
#muscle
